  },
  "contentData": [
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "e0c934fe-087e-4521-9176-9a0723b8b34c",
      "udi": "umb://element/c048a192d32d4082801c6c328b294944",
      "traction": [
        "Geographical"
      ],
      "descriptionOfEnablingFactor": "<p>Shanghai's population grew steeply, generating a need for an efficient public transport system. </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "e0c934fe-087e-4521-9176-9a0723b8b34c",
      "udi": "umb://element/c6477273ae5c44a785fd6fd6a66c51f2",
      "traction": [
        "Other"
      ],
      "descriptionOfEnablingFactor": "<p>Air quality is a significant concern for citizens, incentivising policy makers to reduce air pollution.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "e0c934fe-087e-4521-9176-9a0723b8b34c",
      "udi": "umb://element/d9b6ffd1d8f54c89aa4b12e1134a85fa",
      "traction": [
        "Behavioural and socio-cultural"
      ],
      "descriptionOfEnablingFactor": "<p>Traffic congestion and population density incentivise modal shift and ridesharing initiatives. In 2015, commute time for inhabitants of Shanghai were among the highest in China, with a mean travel time of 50 minutes and distance of 19 km, according to Ly (2020).</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "e0c934fe-087e-4521-9176-9a0723b8b34c",
      "udi": "umb://element/f1f2597ba8354f1bafd56d371c447c51",
      "traction": [
        "End-use technology adoption/infrustructure"
      ],
      "descriptionOfEnablingFactor": "<p>The development of low-rise, high-density blocks create an adequate environment for public and non-motorised means of transportation to develop. Similarly, the grid planning of the city is an enabler for the development of an efficient public transportation system. </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "e0c934fe-087e-4521-9176-9a0723b8b34c",
      "udi": "umb://element/d699e713a4fc447784b8ce163cfe7b00",
      "traction": [
        "Institutional framework and governance structure"
      ],
      "descriptionOfEnablingFactor": "<p>The Shanghai Transportation and Port Development Research Center plays a vital role in enhancing local policy making by researching policies from other cities and gathering data. This approach enables institutions to evaluate the viability and applicability of various policy options. Additionally, the government actively solicits public feedback on transportation policies.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "e0c934fe-087e-4521-9176-9a0723b8b34c",
      "udi": "umb://element/8cf081ec2f6642b09e7ea89e06c71b7f",
      "traction": [
        "Institutional framework and governance structure"
      ],
      "descriptionOfEnablingFactor": "<p>Shanghai's approach to transportation governance stands out as more proactive, transparent, and innovation-oriented compared to Beijing's 'problem-driven' approach, according to a survey conducted by Chun et al. (2019).</p>"
    }
  ],
  "settingsData": []
}]]></Value>
    </caseCountryBlockList>
    <caseIntroduction>
      <Value><![CDATA[<p>"Shanghai's rapid urbanisation has spurred inventive transportation policies. The introduction of a license plate auction system aimed at reducing traffic congestion resulted in slower car ownership growth compared to the national average. </p>
<p>Complementing policies implemented in Shanghai aimed at enhancing public transport and promoting modal shifts in line with transit-oriented development principles. Consequently, the annual ridership percentage for rail transport surged from 2% in 1995 to an impressive 45% in 2015, effectively addressing congestion while fostering sustainable urban mobility."</p>]]></Value>
    </caseIntroduction>
    <caseLockInBlockList>
      <Value><![CDATA[{
  "layout": {
    "Umbraco.BlockList": [
      {
        "contentUdi": "umb://element/b22e2e42f1684d579d02f73e9cd354ca"
      },
      {
